               <p>MARY MILNER. I live with Mr. Thomas Ling, near <placeName id="t18310407-124-crimeloc689">Fitzroy-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-124-crimeloc689" type="placeName" value="Fitzroy-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-124-crimeloc689" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-124-off687 t18310407-124-crimeloc689"></join>. On Sunday morning, the 13th of March, about half-past six o'clock, I missed these articles from the area; I had seen them at eleven o'clock on Saturday night - I saw the prisoner at the office on Monday morning; I could swear to all the property taken.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM PRICHARD. I saw the prisoner in Tottenham-street at half-past six o'clock on Sunday morning, with a basket - he said it was some meat and other things, which he had brought from his mistress in York-street, Regent's-park, and he was going to take them home to Titchfield-street - I showed the property to the witnesses on Monday.</p>
               <p>ANN HARDING. I live with Mr. 
               <persName id="t18310407-124-person1062">
                  Robert 
                  Mason
               <interp inst="t18310407-124-person1062" type="surname" value="Mason"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-124-person1062" type="given" value="Robert"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-124-person1062" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , in the same house, at No. 31. Saville-street. There were 3lbs. of mutton of my master's, which was taken from the same safe - I saw it again, and knew it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. A young man asked me to carry the basket.</p>
